The Autumn Budget confirmed planned DHSC TDEL of £201.9bn in 2024/25, made up of RDEL (£190.1bn) and CDEL (£11.8 bn). This is £13.4bn higher than announced in the Spring Budget. Out of the £190.1 bn DHSC RDEL, £181.4 bn is for the day-to-day running of NHS England.
Between 2023/24 and 2025/26, the total budget for health care is projected to see a real-terms increase of 3.7% per year. Planned RDEL and CDEL spend are projected to rise by 3.3% and 10.9% respectively.

BOX ON METHODOLOGICAL NOTES AND CAVEATS

How does funding compare to historical levels?

Figure 1 shows the real-terms growth rates in total health care funding over the past 40 years. The planned increase in funding over the next two years (3.7%) is slightly below the pre-Covid long-term average (3.8%). However, it is the highest year-on-year rise in funding since 2010 excluding COVID-19 and is higher than the average annual growth rate of 1.4% in the decade before the pandemic (from 2010 to 2019). 
Figure 1: Average real-terms growth in total health spending (DHSC TDEL) by government
  
Is funding enough to meet the pressures facing the health services?

Figure 2 illustrates the impact of adjusting for inflation and changes to the population size and age structure on the NHS spending growth rate per year. Since 2013/14, the real-terms growth rate in NHS spending is 3.1% per year.
Health care use typically increases with age. The Office for National Statistics (ONS) recently revised its population estimates upwards. The population of England is now projected to be 2.0% higher in 2025/26 than in 2023/24 (1.0% growth per year), with a rising share of the population above retirement age. Currently, planned NHS spend per head announced in the Autumn Budget is projected to grow by 1.7% per year from 2023/24 to 2025/26 after accounting for both population growth and ageing. This is lower than the real-terms growth rate of 2.2% from 2013/14 to 2023/24, but higher than the pre-pandemic trend (1.0% from 2013/14 to 2018/19). 
Figure 2: NHSE RDEL (cumulative % increase relative to 2013/14)
 

Conclusion

The additional funding announced for this year and next will help to stabilise services and could enable the government to make some progress on its ambitions for the NHS. The increase in capital investment is particularly welcome and begins to reverse years of underinvestment that has reduced NHS productivity and resulted in a spiralling backlog of maintenance and repairs. 
However, several unknowns remain, including the impact of future staff pay increases and the extent to which the government will cover the cost of the rise to employer’s National Insurance contributions. This could yet reduce the spending power of the additional funding announced and have a substantial impact on the 2025/26 budget. 
More broadly, these funding increases will need to be sustained throughout the rest of the parliament and beyond to meet rising demand and deliver improvements to services. Improving productivity will also need to be a key focus to ensure the new funding stretches as far as possible and to meet a challenging productivity target.
The focus now shifts to next year’s Spending Review and the government’s 10-year health plan to deliver the investment and reform needed to meet the government’s ambitions to improve the NHS.
